entry.title: [execCommand] Fix `RebalanceWhitespaceOnTextSubstring`
entry.content:
This patch fixes `RebalanceWhitespaceOnTextSubstring` when

`white-space: pre-line`.



It checks `white-space: preserve` and returns early if so in

`CanRebalance`[1], then replace consecutive collapsible white

spaces, but it should not handle new lines as collapsible

white spaces when `white-space: pre-line`.



This CL matches the WebKit behavior at:

https://bugs.webkit.org/show_bug.cgi?id=252226



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/renderer/core/editing/commands/composite_edit_command.cc;l=703?q=CompositeEditCommand::CanRebalance&ss=chromium%2Fchromium%2Fsrc

entry.title: Use HandleKeyboardActivation rather than duplicating its code.
entry.content:
This chunk of code originated in HTMLButtonElement. In

https://crrev.com/8ebbf509126641fea90b694a58a3f98689d94cb8 it was copied

from HTMLButtonElement into HTMLSummaryElement (with no indication of

copying left in the code). In

https://crrev.com/93823ec8ea86211c97bf16a1e8bd0285b3a20189 the original

HTMLButtonElement version was refactored into

HTMLElement::HandleKeyboardActivation so that it could be shared with

HTMLPortalElement.



This change makes HTMLSummaryElement share that refactored version

rather than maintaining its own copy. Thankfully, the code is still

identical, other than the refactoring that was done to make it a

separate method.



There is also a more heavily refactored version of this in

BaseCheckableInputType and in KeyboardClickableInputTypeView that I'm

not trying to refactor here. The former was refactored out of

HTMLInputElement in

https://crrev.com/1e961c5625c998a178a3addc6ca60596e8c4b6b3 and the

latter was copied, likely from the former, in

https://crrev.com/4ac48dd80b65c4b827dee77a3562a2f414d0fe85. (Both the

original HTMLButtonElement and original HTMLInputElement versions mostly

originated in

https://crrev.com/689f576a65ae1a10943ba98b10621dec830d1e52.)



(In the future I would like to fix some bugs in this code, so it's

useful to have it in fewer places.)

entry.title: Moving `IsTabClosable` function out of `TabStripModel`
entry.content:
This CL moves the pinned home app specific check implemented in

`IsTabClosable` outside of the `TabStripModel`. This check is not,

as suggested by the location, a check that should hold for all

tabs but is specific to a few specific paths of closing a pinned

home app tab.



This insight comes from two reverts on this CL [1] (due to failing tast

tests) and the explicit statement in this bug [2] that for example for

terminal apps the tab must still be closable. Therefore this check

should not be globally done in the `TabStripModel`.



[1] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4650749

[2] https://buganizer.corp.google.com/issues/289870746

entry.title: Revert "Force load advapi32.dll in browser_tests.exe"
entry.content:
This reverts commit c5af1c29bd19331a163445cdcbae53a6ade07555.



Reason for revert: This change failed to fix the test failures and

is made fully obsolete by the actual fix in crrev.com/c/4673067.



Original change's description:

> Force load advapi32.dll in browser_tests.exe

>

> advapi32.dll is supposed to be delay loaded in chrome.exe, but not in

> chrome.dll. browser_tests.exe basically contains _both_ of these and it

> inherits the delay load of advapi32.dll while inheriting the desire for

> it to not be delay loaded from chrome.dll.

>

> In normal release builds this works fine as advapi32.dll is actually

> loaded before main() is even reached. However in asan builds it appears

> to not reliably be loaded earlier enough, leading to delay-load

> failures.

>

> This change attempts to address that by loading it early in

> browser_test's main(). This should also let crrev.com/c/4637485 be

> relanded.

entry.title: [execCommand] Support `keyUp()` and `keyDown()` in action sequences
entry.content:
This patch implements a short-term solution for `keyUp()` and

`keyDown()` in action sequences. As in crbug.com/893480, the

long-term solution is to move to webdriver, but some tests

need to be fixed before the long-term solution.



This patch does this by following changes:

1. The `testdriver-vendor.js` determines whether it's a key

actions or pointer actions, and dispatch key actions to

`EventSender` instead of `gpuBenchmarking`.

`EventSender` already has logic necessary to implement this,

and it's already used for `send_keys()` testdriver function.

This patch shares the logic with it.

2. `EventSender` has two new functions: `KeyDownOnly` and

`KeyUp`, to support `keyDown()` and `keyUp()` actions

respectively.

Note, `EventSender::KeyDown()` already exists, which sends

both key-down and key-up events. This is currently used by

hundreds of tests, hence the naming above avoids conflicts.



One limitation in this short-term solution is that one action

sequence can't contain both key and pointer actions. From the

test result, there is one such test. Such test is still not

testable with this patch, but this patch turns 43 untestable

tests to testable.
